# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: digital-camera
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:digital-camera/120-film] 120 film was introduced by Kodak for their Brownie No.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] 2 in 1901 and originally intended for amateur photography but was later superseded in this role by 135 film (35mm).
[src:digital-camera/120-film] 120 film survives to this day as the only medium format film that is readily available to both professionals and amateur enthusiasts from most major film manufacturers.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] 120's sister format **220**, introduced in 1965, is largely the same as 120, but is twice the length.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Many cameras which shoot 120 are also designed to shoot 220, although older 120 cameras that use frame number windows are unsuitable for 220, as it lacks the backing paper that 120 has.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Like 620, new rolls of 220 roll film are not produced by many manufacturers.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The 120 film format is a roll film which is nominally between 60.7 mm and 61.7 mm wide.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Most modern films made today are roughly 61 mm (2.4 inches) wide.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The film is held in an open spool originally made of wood with metal flanges, later with all-metal, and finally with all-plastic.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The length of the film is nominally between 820 millimetres (32 in) and 850 millimetres (33 in), according to the ISO 732:2000 standard.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] However, some films may be as short as 760 millimetres (30 in).
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The film is attached to a piece of backing paper longer and slightly wider than the film.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The backing paper protects the film while it is wound on the spool, with enough extra length to allow loading and unloading the roll in daylight without exposing any of the film.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Frame number markings for three standard image formats (6×4.5, 6×6, and 6×9 [4:3, 1:1, and 2:3 aspect ratios]; see below) are printed on the backing paper.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The 220 format was introduced in 1965 and is the same width as 120 film, but with about double the length of film and thus twice the number of possible exposures per roll.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Unlike 120 film, however, there is no backing paper behind the film itself, just a leader and a trailer.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] This results in a longer film on the same spool, but there are no printed frame numbers.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Because of this, 220 film cannot be used in cameras that rely on reading frame numbers through a red window.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Also, since the film alone is thinner than a film with a backing paper, a special pressure plate may be required to achieve optimal focus if the film is registered against its back side.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Some cameras capable of using both 120 and 220 film will have a two position adjustment of the pressure plate (e.g. the Yashica-Mat 124G, Pentax 6x7, Mamiya C220 or Mamiya C330) while others will require different film backs e.g. the Pentax 645 or Kowa Six.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The specifications for 120 and 220 film are defined in the ISO 732 standard.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Earlier editions of ISO 732 also provided international standards for the 127 and 620 film formats.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The 6×9 frame has the same aspect ratio as the standard 24×36 mm frame of 135 film.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The 6×7 frame enlarges almost exactly to 8×10 inch paper, for which reason its proponents call it "ideal format".
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The square 6x6 format is commonly used in twin-lens reflex cameras such as the Rolleiflex.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] 6×4.5 is the smallest and least expensive roll-film frame size.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The wide 6×12, 6×17, and 6×24 cm frames are produced by special-purpose panoramic cameras.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Most of these cameras use lenses intended for large format cameras for simplicity of construction.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Cameras using 120 film will often combine the numbers of the frame size in the name e.g.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The number '6' in general, and the word 'six' are also commonly used in naming cameras e.g.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The **105** format was introduced by Kodak in 1898 for their first folding camera and was the original 6×9 cm format roll film.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The **117** format was introduced by Kodak in 1900 for their first Brownie camera, the No.1 Brownie, 6×6 cm format.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] These formats used the same width film as 120 film, but with slightly different spools.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The 105 spool has a much wider flange, similar to the 116 spool, while the 117 spool's flange is slightly narrower than the 120.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The 105 and 620 spools also have much thinner flanges than the 117 and 120 spools (0.635 mm (0.0250 in) vs.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] 1.524 mm (0.0600 in)); as a result, an unmodified 120 spool will not fit a camera designed for 105 film, such as a No.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] 1 Folding Pocket Kodak, as the overall length between the *outside* of the flanges is too long to fit the width of the film chamber.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The **620** format was introduced by Kodak in 1931 as an intended alternative to 120.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Although mostly used by Kodak cameras, it became very popular.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Hence the 620 is sometimes referred to as "small hole" 6×6 or 6×9 as opposed to 120 "large hole".
[src:digital-camera/120-film] The 620 format was discontinued by Kodak in 1995, but it is possible to rewind 120 film onto a 620 spool in the darkroom for use in 620 cameras.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] According to Kodak, the narrower metal spool allowed building smaller cameras.
[src:digital-camera/120-film] Nonetheless the 120 format cast-metal bodied Voigtländer Perkeo remains smaller than any 620 format camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The term 135 was introduced by Kodak in 1934 as a designation for 35 mm film specifically for still photography, perforated with Kodak Standard perforations.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] It quickly grew in popularity, surpassing 120 film by the late 1960s to become the most popular photographic film size.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Despite competition from formats such as 120, 828, 126, 110, and APS, it remains the most popular film size today.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The size of the 135 film frame with its frame's aspect ratio of 2:3 has been adopted by many high-end digital single-lens reflex and digital mirrorless cameras, commonly referred to as "full frame".
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Even though the format is much smaller than historical medium format and large format film, being historically referred to as *miniature format* or *small format*, it is much larger than image sensors in most compact cameras and smartphone cameras.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The engineering standard for this film is controlled by ISO 1007 titled '135-size film and magazine'.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The 135 film size is derived from earlier still cameras using lengths of 35 mm movie film, which had the same size but with different perforations.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The 35 mm film standard for motion picture film was established in Thomas Edison's lab by William Kennedy Laurie Dickson.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Dickson took 70 mm film stock supplied by George Eastman's Eastman Kodak Company.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The 70 mm film was cut lengthwise into two equal width (35 mm) strips, spliced together end to end, and then perforated along both edges.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The original picture size was 18×24 mm (half the full frame size later used in still photography).
[src:digital-camera/135-film] There were four perforations on each side of a motion picture frame.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] While the Leica camera popularized the format, several 35 mm still cameras used perforated movie film before the Leica was introduced in the 1920s.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The first patent for one was issued to Leo, Audobard, and Baradat in England in 1908.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The first full-scale production camera was the Homéos, a stereo camera produced by Jules Richard in 1913 and sold until 1920.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] It took 18x24 mm stereo pairs and used two Tessar lenses.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In 1909, the French Étienne Mollier designed a device for small-format photography, the "Cent-Vues", which used the 35 mm perforated film to take consecutive hundred views in 18×24 mm.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] He manufactured it, won the gold medal in the Concours Lépine, and in 1910 sold at a small scale and without much success.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The first big-selling 35 mm still camera was the American Tourist Multiple, which also appeared in 1913, at a cost of $175 (~5,600 US Dollars in 2024) The first camera to take full-frame 24×36 mm exposures seems to be the Simplex, introduced in the U.S. in 1914.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] It took either 800 half-frame or 400 full-frame shots on 50 ft (15.2 m) rolls.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The Minigraph, by Levy-Roth of Berlin, another half-frame small camera was sold in Germany in 1915.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The patent for the Debrie Sept camera, a combination 35 mm still and movie camera was issued in 1918; the camera sold from 1922.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The Furet camera made and sold in France in 1923 took full-frame 24x36 mm negatives, and was the first cheap small 35 mm camera of similar appearance to more modern models.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The Leica Camera designed by Oskar Barnack used 35 mm film, and proved that a format as small as 24 mm × 36 mm was suitable for professional photography.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Although Barnack designed his prototype camera around 1913, the first experimental production run of ur-Leicas (Serial No.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Full-scale production of the Leica did not begin until 1925.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] While by that time, there were at least a dozen other 35 mm cameras available, the Leica was a success.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] It came to be associated with the format, mostly because of this 35 mm popularity, as well as the entire company legacy.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Early Leica cameras are considered highly collectable items.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The original Leica prototype holds the record as being the world's most expensive camera, selling for €2.16 million in 2012.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In the earliest days, the photographer had to load the film into reusable cassettes and, at least for some cameras, cut the film leader.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In 1934, Kodak introduced a *135* daylight-loading single-use cassette.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] This cassette was engineered so that it could be used in both Leica and Zeiss Ikon Contax cameras along with the camera for which it was invented, namely the Kodak Retina camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The Retina camera and this daylight loading cassette were the invention of Dr.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] August Nagel's company in December, 1931, and began marketing the *Kodak Retina* in the summer of 1934.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The first Kodak Retina camera was a Typ 117.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The 35 mm Kodak Retina camera line remained in production until 1969.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Kodak also introduced a line of American made cameras that were simpler and more economical than the Retina.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Argus, too, made a long-lived range of 35 mm cameras; notably the Argus C3.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Kodak launched 135-format Kodachrome colour film in 1936.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] AGFA followed with the introduction of *Agfacolor Neu* later in the same year.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The designations *235* and *435* refer to 35 mm film in daylight-loading spools, that could be loaded into Contax or Leica style reusable cassettes, respectively, without need of a darkroom.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The *335* was a daylight loading spool for the 24 × 23 mm stereo format.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Reflex viewfinders, both twin-and single-lens, had been used with earlier cameras using plates and rollfilm.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The first 35 mm single-lens reflex (SLR) was the Kine Exakta, introduced in 1936.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] World War II interrupted development of the type.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] After the war, Exakta resumed development and the Contax S model with the now familiar pentaprism viewing feature was introduced in 1949.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In the 1950s, the SLR also began to be produced in Japan by such companies as Asahi and Miranda.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Asahi's Pentax introduced the instant-return mirror, important for the popularity of SLRs; until then, the viewfinder on an SLR camera blanked as the mirror sprang out of the optical path just before taking the picture, returning when the film was wound on.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Nikon's F model, introduced in March 1959, was a system camera that greatly improved the quality and utility of 35 mm format cameras, encouraging professionals (especially photojournalists) to switch from larger format cameras to the versatile, rugged, and fast SLR design.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Numerous other film formats waxed and waned in popularity, but by the 1970s, interchangeable-lens SLR cameras and smaller rangefinders, from expensive Leicas to "point-and-shoot" pocket cameras, were all using 35 mm film, and manufacturers had proliferated.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Colour films improved, both for print negatives and reversal slides, while black-and-white films offered smoother grain and faster speeds than previously available.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Since 35 mm was preferred by both amateur and professional photographers, makers of film stock have long offered the widest range of different film speeds and types in the format.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The DX film-speed encoding system was introduced in the 1980s, as were single-use cameras pre-loaded with 35 mm film and using plastic lenses of reasonable enough quality to produce acceptable snapshots.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Automated all-in-one processing and printing machines made 35 mm developing easier and less expensive, so that quality colour prints became available not only from photographic specialty stores, but also from supermarkets, drugstores, and big box retailers, often in less than an hour.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In 1996, a smaller format called Advanced Photo System (APS) was introduced by a consortium of photographic companies in an attempt to supersede 135 film.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Due in part to its small negative size, APS was not taken seriously as a professional format, despite the production of APS SLRs.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In the point-and-shoot markets at which the format was primarily aimed, it enjoyed moderate initial success, but still never rivalled the market penetration of 135.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Within five years of its launch, cheap digital compact cameras started becoming widely available, and APS sales plummeted.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Introductory 35 mm SLRs, compact film point-and-shoot cameras, and single-use cameras continue to be built and sold by a number of makers.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Leica introduced the digital Leica M8 rangefinder in 2007, but continues to make its M series rangefinder film cameras and lenses.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] A digital camera back for the Leica R9 SLR camera was discontinued in 2007.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] On March 25, 2009, Leica discontinued the R9 SLR and R-series lenses.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] By the early 2020s, film photography, particularly 35 mm photography, was experiencing a resurgence in popularity.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In a 2021 PetaPixel survey, 75% of respondents expressed interest in newly manufactured analog cameras.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Kodak reported in 2022 that it was having trouble keeping up with demand for 35 mm film.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In 2024, the Pentax 17 and the Aflie TYCH+ 35 mm cameras were released, both using the half-frame format to conserve film.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Retrospekt and Mattel put out the Malibu Barbie FC-11 35 mm camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In September 2024, MiNT Camera took pre-orders for the Rollei 35AF, an update of the Rollei 35.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Kodak offered six 35 mm film cameras for sale as of October 2024, including the Ektar H35N, another half-frame camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Individual rolls of 135 film are enclosed in single-spool, light-tight, metal cassettes, also known as film canisters, to allow cameras to be loaded in daylight.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The film is clipped or taped to a spool and exits via a slot lined with flocking.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The end of the film is cut on one side to form a leader.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] It has the same dimensions and perforation pitch as 35 mm movie print film (also called "long pitch", KS-1870, whereas 35 mm professional motion picture camera films are always "short pitch", BH-1866).
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Most cameras require the film to be rewound before the camera is opened.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Some motorized cameras unwind the film fully upon loading and then expose the images in reverse order, returning the film to the cassette; this protects all exposed frames (except the last one or two), should the camera back be accidentally opened; unexposed film gets spoiled, however.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Disposable cameras use the same technique so that the user does not have to rewind.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Since 1983, most film cassettes have been marked with a DX encoding six-digit barcode pattern, which uses a DX number to identify the manufacturer and film type (and thus processing method), and the number of exposures, for the use of photofinishing laboratories.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Conforming cameras detect at least some of these areas; only three contacts are needed to set a light meter for the four most popular film speeds.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The 135 film has been made in several emulsion types and sensitivities (film speeds) described by ISO standards.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Since the introduction of digital cameras the most usual films have colour emulsions of ISO 100/21° to ISO 800/30°.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Films of lower sensitivity (and better picture quality) and higher sensitivity (for low light) are for more specialist purposes.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] There are colour and monochrome films, negative and positive.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Monochrome film is usually panchromatic; orthochromatic has fallen out of use.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Film designed to be sensitive to infrared radiation can be obtained, both monochrome and with false-colour (or pseudocolour) rendition.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] More exotic emulsions have been available in 135 than other roll-film sizes.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The term *135 format* usually refers to a 24×36 mm film format, commonly known as 35 mm format.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The 24×36 mm format is common to higher-end digital image sensors, where it is typically referred to as *full-frame* format.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] On 135 film, the typical cameras produce a frame where the longer dimension of the 24×36 mm frame runs parallel to the length of the film.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The perforation size and pitch are according to the standard specification KS-1870.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] For each frame, the film advances 8 perforations.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] This allows for 2 mm gaps between frames.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Camera models typically have different locations for the sprocket which advances the film.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Therefore, each camera model's frame may vary in position relative to the perforations.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The film is approximately 0.14 mm thick.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Other image formats have been applied to 135 film, such as the half-frame format of 18×24 mm which earned some popularity in the 1960s, and the 24×24 mm of the Robot cameras.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The successful range of Olympus Pen F cameras utilized the smaller half-frame size, allowing the design of a very compact SLR camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Unusual formats include the 24×32 mm and 24×34 mm on the early Nikon rangefinders, and 24×23 mm for use with some stereo cameras.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In 1967, the Soviet KMZ factory introduced a 24×58 mm panoramic format with its Horizont camera (descendants of which are called, in the Roman alphabet, Horizon).
[src:digital-camera/135-film] In 1998, Hasselblad and Fuji introduced a 24×65 mm panoramic format with their XPan/TX-1 camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] There is also a 21×14 mm format used by Tessina subminiature camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The film is available in lengths for varying numbers of exposures.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The standard full-length roll has always been 36 exposures (assuming a standard 24×36 frame size).
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Through about 1980, 20 exposure rolls were the only shorter length with widespread availability.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Since then, 20 exposure rolls have been largely discontinued in favour of 24- and 12-exposure rolls.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] A camera that uses less than the maximum distance between the spools may be able to make one additional exposure.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Self-loading cameras that load the film after being closed don't spoil the additional length provided for conventional loading and can make that additional length available for two or three additional exposures.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The same length can be available for exposure in any camera if it is loaded without exposing the film to light, e.g. in a dark room or a dark bag.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] A 27-exposure disposable camera uses a standard 24-exposure cassette loaded in the dark.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Other, mostly shorter, lengths have been manufactured.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] There have been some 6-, 8-, 10-, and 15-exposure rolls given away as samples, sometimes in disposable cameras, or used by insurance adjusters to document damage claims.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Twelve-exposure rolls have been used widely in the daily press.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Photographers who load their own cassettes can use any length of film – with a thinner film base, up to 45 exposures will fit.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] The Ilford HP black-and-white film, on a thin polyester base, allowed 72 exposures in a single cassette.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] They produced special reels and tanks to allow this to be processed.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Digital sensors are available in various sizes.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Professional DSLR cameras usually use digital image sensors which approximate the dimensions of the 35 mm format, sometimes differing by fractions of a millimetre on one or both dimensions.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Since 2007, Nikon has referred to their 35 mm format by the trade mark FX.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Other makers of 35 mm format digital cameras, including Leica, Sony, and Canon, refer to their 35 mm sensors simply as full frame.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Most consumer DSLR cameras use smaller sensors, with the most popular size being APS-C which measures around 23×15 mm (giving it a crop factor of 1.5–1.6).
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Compact cameras have smaller sensors with a crop factor of around 3 to 6.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Most smartphones (as of 2024) have a default aspect ratio of 4:3 (1.33).
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Mimicking 35mm film in a smartphone requires cropping to a 3:2 (1.5) aspect ratio.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] For an authentic homage, one can apply creative digital filters like the ones commonly used in Instagram that map the colour profile to a characteristic look.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Different brands of 35mm film would achieve the creative colour profile through a chemical process.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] For example Fuji Velvia film gave the photo a characteristic of saturated colours under daylight, high contrast, and exceptional sharpness.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] A true normal lens for 35 mm format would have a focal length of 43 mm, the diagonal measurement of the format.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] However, lenses of 43 mm to 60 mm are commonly considered *normal* lenses for the format, in mass production and popular use.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Common focal lengths of lenses made for the format include 24, 28, 35, 50, 85, 105, and 135 mm.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Most commonly, a 50 mm lens is the one considered *normal*; any lens shorter than this is considered a *wide angle* lens and anything above is considered a *telephoto* lens.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Even then, wide angles shorter than 24 mm is called an *extreme wide angle*.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Lenses above 50 mm but up to about 100 mm are called short telephoto or sometimes, as *portrait telephotos*, from 100 mm to about 200 mm are called *medium* telephotos, and above 300 mm are called *long* telephotos.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] With many smaller formats now common (such as APS-C), lenses are often advertised or marked with their "35 mm equivalent" or "full-frame equivalent" focal length as a mnemonic, due to the historic prevalence of the 35 mm format.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] This 'equivalent' is computed by multiplying (a) the true focal length of the lens by (b) the ratio of the diagonal measurement of the native format to that of the 35 mm format.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] As a result, a lens for an APS-C (18×24 mm) format camera body with a focal length of 40 mm, might be described as "60 mm (35 mm equivalent)".
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Although its true focal length remains 40 mm, its angle of view is equivalent to that of a 60 mm lens on a 35 mm format (24×36 mm) camera.
[src:digital-camera/135-film] Another example is the lens of the 2/3 inch format Fujifilm X10, which is marked with its true zoom range "7.1–28.4 mm" but has a 35 mm-equivalent zoom range of "28–112 mm".
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A **floppy disk**, **diskette**, or **floppy diskette** is a type of disk storage made from a thin, flexible disk coated with a magnetic storage medium.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] It is enclosed in a square or nearly square plastic shell lined with fabric to help remove dust from the spinning disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Floppy disks store digital data, which can be read or written when inserted into a **floppy disk drive** (**FDD**) connected to or built into a computer or other device.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The three most popular formats of floppy disks (and their drives) are the 8-inch, 5¼-inch, and 3½-inch versions.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The first floppy disks, invented and made by IBM in 1971, had a disk diameter of 8 inches (200 mm).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Subsequently, the 5¼-inch (130 mm) and then the 3½-inch (90 mm) became a ubiquitous form of data storage and data transfer into the first years of the 21st century.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] By the end of the 1980s, 5¼-inch (130 mm) disks had been superseded by 3½-inch (90 mm) disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] During this time, PCs frequently came equipped with drives of both sizes.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] By the mid-1990s, 5¼-inch drives had virtually disappeared, the 3½-inch disk became the dominant format.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The advantages of the 3½-inch (90 mm) disk were its higher capacity, smaller physical size, and its rigid case which provided better protection from dirt and other environmental risks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Floppy disks were so common in late 20th-century culture that many electronic and software programs continue to use save icons that look like floppy disks well into the 21st century, as a form of skeuomorphic design.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Industry observers categorize floppy disks and floppy disk drives according to size and capacity with four major categories being 8 inches (200 mm), 5.25 inches (130 mm), 3.5 inches (90 mm) and high-capacity floppy disks and floppy disk drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] There were in addition, variant products that did not fit these categories.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The distinguishing characteristic between the high-capacity products and their lower capacity brethren, frequently categorized as standard floppies, was the use of servomechanisms to increase the number of tracks and thereby increase capacity.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] While the original IBM 8 inches (200 mm) disk was actually so defined, the other sizes are defined in millimeters, their names being but rough approximations.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Different sizes of floppy disks are mechanically incompatible, and disks can fit only one size of drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Drive assemblies with both 3.5 inches (90 mm) and 5.25 inches (130 mm) slots were available during the transition period between the sizes, but they contained two separate drive mechanisms.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] As computer platforms began to form, attempts were made at interchangeability.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Apple's later 1.44 MB high-density 3.5 inches (90 mm) drives (marketed as the SuperDrive) could read, write, and format IBM PC–compatible floppy disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] However, few IBM-compatible computers were able to read or write Apple-formatted floppy disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The limitation was due not to the 3.5 inches (90 mm) drive mechanism itself, but to the disk controller and its lack of support for Apple's GCR (Group Coded Recording) encoding used on 400 kB and 800 kB Macintosh disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] 8 in (200 mm), 5.25 in (130 mm) and 3.5 in (90 mm) drives were manufactured in a variety of sizes, most to fit standardized drive bays.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Alongside the common disk sizes were non-classical sizes for specialized systems.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The first commercial floppy disks, developed in the late 1960s, were 8 inches (200 mm) in diameter; they became commercially available in 1971 as a component of IBM products and both drives and disks were then sold separately starting in 1972 by Memorex and others.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] These disks and associated drives were produced and improved upon by IBM and other companies such as Memorex, Shugart Associates, and Burroughs Corporation.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The term "floppy disk" appeared in print as early as 1970, and although IBM announced its first media as the *Type 1 Diskette* in 1973, the industry continued to use the terms "floppy disk" or "floppy".
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Floppy disks of the first standard are 8 inches (200 mm) in diameter, protected by a flexible plastic jacket.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] It was a read-only device used by IBM as a way of loading microcode.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Read/write floppy disks and their drives became available in 1972, but it was IBM's 1973 introduction of the 3740 data entry system that began the establishment of floppy disks, called by IBM the *Diskette 1*, as an industry standard for information interchange.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Diskettes formatted for this system stored 242,944 bytes.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Early microcomputers used for engineering, business, or word processing often used one or more 8-inch disk drives for removable storage; the CP/M operating system was developed for microcomputers with 8-inch drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The family of 8-inch (200 mm) disks and drives increased over time and later versions could store up to 1.2 MB; many microcomputer applications did not need that much capacity on one disk, so a smaller size disk with lower-cost media and drives was feasible.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The 5.25-inch (130 mm) drive succeeded the 8-inch (200 mm) in many applications, and developed to the same storage capacity as the larger 8-inch (200 mm) size, using higher-density media and recording techniques.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In 1976, Shugart Associates introduced the 5.25-inch (130 mm) floppy disk drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] By 1978, there were more than ten manufacturers producing such drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] There were competing floppy disk formats, with hard- and soft-sector versions and encoding schemes such as differential Manchester encoding (DM), modified frequency modulation (MFM), M2FM and group coded recording (GCR).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The 5.25-inch (130 mm) format displaced the 8-inch (200 mm) one for most uses, and the hard-sectored disk format disappeared.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The most common capacity of the 5.25-inch (130 mm) format in DOS-based PCs was 360 KB (368,640 bytes) for the Double-Sided Double-Density (DSDD) format using MFM encoding.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In 1984, IBM introduced its PC/AT with the 1.2 MB (1,228,800 bytes) dual-sided 5.25-inch (130 mm) floppy disk, but it never became very popular.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] IBM started using the 720 KB double density 3.5-inch (90 mm) microfloppy disk on its Convertible laptop computer in 1986 and the 1.44 MB (1,474,560 bytes) high-density version with the IBM Personal System/2 (PS/2) line in 1987.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] These disk drives could be added to older PC models.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Throughout the early 1980s, limits of the 5.25-inch (130 mm) format became clear.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Originally designed to be more practical than the 8-inch (200 mm) format, it was considered too large; as the quality of recording media grew, data could be stored in a smaller area.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Several solutions were developed, with drives at 2-, 2½-, 3-, 3¼-, 3½- and 4-inches (and Sony's 90 mm × 94 mm (3.54 in × 3.70 in) disk) offered by various companies.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The established market for the 5.25-inch (130 mm) format made it difficult for these mutually incompatible new formats to gain significant market share.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A variant on the Sony design, introduced in 1983 by many manufacturers, was then rapidly adopted.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The head gap of an 80‑track high-density (1.2 MB in the MFM format) 5.25-inch (130 mm) drive (a.k.a.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] *mini diskette*, *Mini disk*, or *Minifloppy*) is smaller than that of a 40‑track double-density (360 KB if double-sided) drive but can also format, read and write 40‑track disks provided the controller supports double stepping or has a switch to do so.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A blank 40‑track disk formatted and written on an 80‑track drive can be taken to its native drive without problems, and a disk formatted on a 40‑track drive can be used on an 80‑track drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Disks written on a 40‑track drive and then updated on an 80 track drive become unreadable on any 40‑track drives due to track width incompatibility.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Single-sided disks were coated on both sides.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The reason usually given for the higher price was that double sided disks were certified error-free on both sides of the media.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Double-sided disks could be used in some drives for single-sided disks, as long as an index signal was not needed.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This was done one side at a time, by turning them over (flippy disks); more expensive dual-head drives which could read both sides without turning over were later produced, and eventually became used universally.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In the early 1980s, many manufacturers introduced smaller floppy drives and media in various formats.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Single-sided drives of the consortium design first shipped in 1983, and double-sided in 1984.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The double-sided, high-density 1.44 MB (actually 1440 KiB = 1.41 MiB or 1.47 MB) disk drive, which would become the most popular, first shipped in 1986.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The first Macintosh computers used single-sided 3.5-inch (90 mm) floppy disks, but with 400 kB formatted capacity.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] These were followed in 1986 by double-sided 800 kB floppies.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The higher capacity was achieved at the same recording density by varying the disk-rotation speed with head position so that the linear speed of the disk was closer to constant.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Later Macs could also read and write 1.44 MB HD disks in PC format with fixed rotation speed.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Higher capacities were similarly achieved by Acorn's RISC OS (800 kB for DD, 1,600 kB for HD) and AmigaOS (880 kB for DD, 1,760 kB for HD).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Most 3.5-inch (90 mm) disks have a rectangular hole in one corner which, if obstructed, write-enables the disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A sliding detented piece can be moved to block or reveal the part of the rectangular hole that is sensed by the drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The HD 1.44 MB disks have a second, unobstructed hole in the opposite corner that identifies them as being of that capacity.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In IBM-compatible PCs, higher-density 3.5-inch (90 mm) floppy drives can read lower-density media, but writing and formatting across densities has reliability issues and was not officially supported by manufacturers.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Writing at different densities than those at which disks were intended, sometimes by altering the density detection hole, was possible but not supported by manufacturers.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A hole on one side of a 3.5-inch (90 mm) disk can be altered to make some disk drives and operating systems treat the disk as one of higher or lower density, for bidirectional compatibility or economic reasons.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Some computers, such as the PS/2 and Acorn Archimedes, ignored these holes altogether.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Generally, the term floppy disk persisted, even though later style floppy disks have a rigid case around an internal floppy disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A number of attempts were made by various companies to introduce newer floppy-disk formats, frequently characterized as a "**super floppy,**" with many based on the standard 3½-inch physical form while offering much higher capacity.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Many of these products provide the ability to read and write standard DD and HD disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] None of these ever reached the point where it could be assumed that every current PC would have one, and they were later largely replaced first by optical disc burners and then by flash storage.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In 1990, an attempt was made to standardize details for a 20MB 3½-inch format floppy.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] At the time, "three different technologies that are not interchangeable" existed.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] One major goal was that the to-be-developed standard drive be backward compatible: that it be able to read 720 KB and 1.44 MB floppies.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Other smaller floppy sizes were proposed, especially for portable or pocket-sized devices that needed a smaller storage device.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] None of these sizes achieved much market success.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In the mid-1990s, mechanically incompatible higher-density floppy disks were introduced, like the Iomega Zip disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Adoption was limited by the competition between proprietary formats and the need to buy expensive drives for computers where the disks would be used.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In some cases, failure in market penetration was exacerbated by the release of higher-capacity versions of the drive and media being not backward-compatible with the original drives, dividing the users between new and old adopters.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Consumers were wary of making costly investments into unproven and rapidly changing technologies, so none of the technologies became the established standard.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Apple introduced the iMac G3 in 1998 with a CD-ROM drive but no floppy drive; this made USB-connected floppy drives popular accessories, as the iMac came without any writable removable media device.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Recordable CDs were touted as an alternative, because of the greater capacity, compatibility with existing CD-ROM drives, and—with the advent of re-writeable CDs and packet writing—a similar reusability as floppy disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] However, CD-R/RWs remained mostly an archival medium, not a medium for exchanging data or editing files on the medium itself, because there was no common standard for packet writing which allowed for small updates.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Other formats, such as magneto-optical discs, had the flexibility of floppy disks combined with greater capacity, but remained niche due to costs.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] High-capacity backward compatible floppy technologies became popular for a while and were sold as an option or even included in standard PCs, but in the long run, their use was limited to professionals and enthusiasts.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Flash-based USB thumb drives finally provided a practical and popular replacement that supported traditional file systems and all common usage scenarios of floppy disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] As opposed to other solutions, no new drive type or special software was required that impeded adoption, since all that was necessary was an already common USB port.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In 2002, most manufacturers still provided floppy disk drives as standard equipment to meet user demand for file transfer and an emergency boot device, as well as for the general secure feeling of having the familiar device.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] By this time, the retail cost of a floppy drive had fallen to around $20 (equivalent to $36 in 2025), so there was little financial incentive to omit the device from a system.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Subsequently, enabled by the widespread support for USB flash drives and BIOS boot, manufacturers and retailers progressively reduced the availability of floppy disk drives as standard equipment.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In February 2003, Dell, one of the leading personal computer vendors, announced that floppy drives would no longer be pre-installed on Dell Dimension home computers, although they were still available as a selectable option and purchasable as an aftermarket OEM add-on.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] By January 2007, only 2% of computers sold in stores contained built-in floppy disk drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Floppy disks are used for emergency boots in aging systems lacking support for other bootable media and for BIOS updates, since most BIOS and firmware programs can still be executed from bootable floppy disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] If BIOS updates fail or become corrupt, floppy drives can sometimes be used to perform a recovery.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The music and theatre industries still use equipment requiring standard floppy disks (e.g. synthesizers, samplers, drum machines, sequencers, and lighting consoles).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Industrial automation equipment such as programmable machinery and industrial robots may not have a USB interface; data and programs are then loaded from disks, damageable in industrial environments.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This equipment may not be replaced due to cost or requirement for continuous availability; existing software emulation and virtualization do not solve this problem because a customized operating system is used that has no drivers for USB devices.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Hardware floppy disk emulators can be made to interface floppy-disk controllers to a USB port that can be used for flash drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In May 2016, the United States Government Accountability Office released a report that covered the need to upgrade or replace legacy computer systems within federal agencies.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] According to this document, old IBM Series/1 minicomputers running on 8-inch floppy disks are still used to coordinate "the operational functions of the United States' nuclear forces".
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The government planned to update some of the technology by the end of the 2017 fiscal year.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Use in Japan's government ended in 2024.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Windows 10 and Windows 11 no longer come with drivers for floppy disk drives (both internal and external).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] However, they will still support them with a separate device driver provided by Microsoft.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The British Airways Boeing 747-400 fleet, up to its retirement in 2020, used 3½-inch floppy disks to load avionics software.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Sony, who had been in the floppy disk business since 1983, ended domestic sales of all six 3½-inch floppy disk models as of March 2011.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] *Wired* magazine called it "the death of the floppy disk." While production of new floppy disk media has ceased, sales and uses of this media from inventories is expected to continue until at least 2026.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The 8-inch and 5¼-inch floppy disks contain a magnetically coated round plastic medium with a large circular hole in the center for a drive's spindle.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The medium is contained in a square plastic cover that has a small oblong opening in both sides to allow the drive's heads to read and write data and a large hole in the center to allow the magnetic medium to spin by rotating it from its middle hole.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Inside the cover are two layers of fabric with the magnetic medium sandwiched in the middle.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The fabric is designed to reduce friction between the medium and the outer cover, and catch particles of debris abraded off the disk to keep them from accumulating on the heads.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The cover is usually a one-part sheet, double-folded with flaps glued or spot-welded together.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A small notch on the side of the disk identifies whether it is writable, as detected by a mechanical switch or photoelectric sensor.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In the 8-inch disk, the notch being covered or not present enables writing, while in the 5¼-inch disk, the notch being present and uncovered enables writing.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Tape may be used over the notch to change the mode of the disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Punch devices were sold to convert read-only 5¼" disks to writable ones, and also to enable writing on the unused side of single-sided disks for computers with single-sided drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The latter worked because single- and double-sided disks typically contained essentially identical actual magnetic media, for manufacturing efficiency.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Disks whose obverse and reverse sides were thus used separately in single-sided drives were known as flippy disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Disk notching 5¼" floppies for PCs was generally only required where users wanted to overwrite original 5¼" disks of store-bought software, which somewhat commonly shipped with no notch present.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Another LED/photo-transistor pair located near the center of the disk detects the *index hole* once per rotation in the magnetic disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Detection occurs whenever the drive's sensor, the holes in the correctly inserted floppy's plastic envelope and a single hole in the rotating floppy disk medium line up.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This mechanism is used to detect the angular start of each track, and whether or not the disk is rotating at the correct speed.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Early 8‑inch and 5¼‑inch disks also had holes for each sector in the enclosed magnetic medium, in addition to the index hole, with the same radial distance from the center, for alignment with the same envelope hole.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] These were termed *hard sectored* disks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Later *soft-sectored* disks have only one index hole in the medium, and sector position is determined by the disk controller or low-level software from patterns marking the start of a sector.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Generally, the same drives are used to read and write both types of disks, with only the disks and controllers differing.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Some operating systems using soft sectors, such as Apple DOS, do not use the index hole, and the drives designed for such systems often lack the corresponding sensor; this was mainly a hardware cost-saving measure.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The core of the 3.5 in (90 mm) disk is the same as the other two disks, but the front has only a label and a small opening for reading and writing data, protected by the shutter—a spring-loaded metal or plastic cover, pushed to the side on entry into the drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Rather than having a hole in the center, it has a metal hub which mates to the spindle of the drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] As with all magnetic storage, it is vulnerable to magnetic fields.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Blank disks have been distributed with an extensive set of warnings, cautioning the user not to expose it to dangerous conditions.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Rough treatment or removing the disk from the drive while the magnetic media is still spinning is likely to cause damage to the disk, drive head, or stored data.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The main technological change for the higher-capacity formats was the addition of tracking information on the disk surface to allow the read/write heads to be positioned more accurately.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Most earlier generations of floppy disks have no such information, so the drives use open loop positioning by a stepper motor in order to position their heads over the desired track.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For good interoperability of disks among drives, this requires precise alignment of the drive heads to a reference standard, somewhat similar to the alignment required to get the best performance out of an audio tape deck.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The newer systems generally use position information on the surfaces of the disk to find the tracks, allowing the track width to be greatly reduced.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] It is considered to be the first actual super floppy.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] and its technology was licensed to a number of companies, who introduced compatible devices as well as even larger-capacity formats.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Physically both the media and cartridge were slightly larger but similar to other 3½-inch media and cartridges.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A linear actuator positioned flying heads over high-capacity media that started at 100 MB and grew to 700 MB.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] to generate light that allows the drive to align its heads on high capacity FD media, initially at 120 MB and subsequently at 240 MB.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] onto a 3½-inch 1,440 kB disk albeit not too reliably.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In addition to the four generations of floppy disks and drives covered in this article there were various other floppy disks (and drives) offered, some were failed attempts to establish a standard for a generation while others were for special applications.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A spindle motor in the drive rotates the magnetic medium at a certain speed, while a stepper motor-operated mechanism moves the magnetic read/write heads radially along the surface of the disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Both read and write operations require the media to be rotating and the head to contact the disk media, an action originally accomplished by a disk-load solenoid.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Later drives held the heads out of contact until a front-panel lever was rotated (5¼-inch) or disk insertion was complete (3½-inch).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] To write data, current is sent through a coil in the head as the media rotates.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The head's magnetic field aligns the magnetization of the particles directly below the head on the media.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] When the current is reversed the magnetization aligns in the opposite direction, encoding one bit of data.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] To read data, the magnetization of the particles in the media induce a tiny voltage in the head coil as they pass under it.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This small signal is amplified and sent to the floppy disk controller, which converts the streams of pulses from the media into data, checks it for errors, and sends it to the host computer system.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A blank unformatted diskette has a coating of magnetic oxide with no magnetic order to the particles.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] During formatting, the magnetizations of the particles are aligned forming tracks, each broken up into sectors, enabling the controller to properly read and write data.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Each sector of data has a header that identifies the sector location on the disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A cyclic redundancy check (CRC) is written into the sector headers and at the end of the user data so that the disk controller can detect potential errors.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In some 5¼-inch drives, insertion of the disk compresses and locks an ejection spring which partially ejects the disk upon opening the catch or lever.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] On Macintosh computers with built-in 3½-inch disk drives, the ejection button is replaced by software controlling an ejection motor which only does so when the operating system no longer needs to access the drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The user could drag the image of the floppy drive to the trash can on the desktop to eject the disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In the case of a power failure or drive malfunction, a loaded disk can be removed manually by inserting a straightened paper clip into a small hole at the drive's front panel, just as one would do with a CD-ROM drive in a similar situation.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The X68000 has soft-eject 5¼-inch drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Some late-generation IBM PS/2 machines have soft-eject 3½-inch disk drives as well for which PC DOS 5.02 and higher includes an `EJECT` command.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Before a disk can be accessed, the drive needs to synchronize its head position with the disk tracks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In either case, the head is moved so that it is approaching track zero position of the disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] When a drive with the sensor has reached track zero, the head stops moving immediately and is correctly aligned.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Drives without a sensor such as the Apple II mechanism attempt to move the head the maximum possible number of positions needed to reach track zero, knowing that once this motion is complete, the head will be positioned over track zero.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This physical striking is responsible for drive clicking during the boot and when disk errors occurred and track zero synchronization was attempted.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] All 8-inch and some 5¼-inch drives use methods to locate sectors, known as either hard sectors or soft sectors, with the small hole in the jacket, off to the side of the spindle hole, used for timing reference.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A light beam sensor detects when a punched hole in the disk is visible through the hole in the jacket.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For a soft-sectored disk, there is only a single hole, which is used to locate the first sector of each track.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For a hard-sectored disk, there are many holes, one for each sector row, plus an additional hole in a half-sector position, that is used to indicate sector zero.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The Apple II computer system is notable in that it does not have an index-hole sensor and ignores the presence of hard or soft sectoring.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Instead, it uses special repeating data synchronization patterns written to the disk between each sector, to assist the computer in finding and synchronizing with the data in each track.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Most 3½-inch drives use a constant speed drive motor and contain the same number of sectors across all tracks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This is sometimes referred to as constant angular velocity.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This allows more sectors to be written to the longer middle and outer tracks as the track length increases.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Floppy disk size is often referred to in inches, even in countries using metric and though the size is defined in metric.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The ANSI specification of 3½-inch disks is entitled in part "90 mm (3.5-inch)" though 90 mm is closer to 3.54 inches.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Formatted capacities are generally set in terms of kilobytes and megabytes.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Data is generally written to floppy disks in sectors (angular blocks) and tracks (concentric rings at a constant radius).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For example, the HD format of 3½-inch floppy disks uses 512 bytes per sector, 18 sectors per track, 80 tracks per side and two sides, for a total of 1,474,560 bytes per disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Some disk controllers can vary these parameters at the user's request, increasing storage on the disk, although they may not be able to be read on machines with other controllers.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For example, Microsoft applications were often distributed on 3½-inch 1.68 MB DMF disks formatted with 21 sectors instead of 18; they could still be recognized by a standard controller.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Constant linear velocity was generally not used on floppy disks, so most computer systems used constant angular velocity (CAV) format, with the disk spinning at a constant speed and the sectors holding the same amount of information on each track regardless of radial location.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A notable exception was Apple, which implemented CLV in early Macintosh computers by spinning the disk more slowly when the head was at the edge, while maintaining the data rate, allowing 400 KB of storage per side and an extra 80 KB on a double-sided disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Because the sectors have constant angular size, the 512 bytes in each sector are compressed more near the disk's center.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] A more space-efficient technique would be to increase the number of sectors per track toward the outer edge of the disk, from 18 to 30 for instance, thereby keeping nearly constant the amount of physical disk space used for storing each sector; an example is zone bit recording.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Apple implemented this in early Macintosh computers by spinning the disk more slowly when the head was at the edge, while maintaining the data rate, allowing 400 KB of storage per side and an extra 80 KB on a double-sided disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This higher capacity came with a disadvantage: the format used a unique drive mechanism and control circuitry, meaning that Mac disks could not be read on other computers.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Apple eventually reverted to constant angular velocity on HD floppy disks with their later machines, still unique to Apple as they supported the older variable-speed formats.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Disk formatting is usually done by a utility program supplied by the computer OS manufacturer; generally, it sets up a file storage directory system on the disk, and initializes its sectors and tracks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Areas of the disk unusable for storage due to flaws can be locked (marked as "bad sectors") so that the operating system does not attempt to use them.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This was time-consuming so many environments had quick formatting which skipped the error checking process.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] When floppy disks were often used, disks pre-formatted for popular computers were sold.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The unformatted capacity of a floppy disk does not include the sector and track headings of a formatted disk; the difference in storage between them depends on the drive's application.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Floppy disk drive and media manufacturers specify the unformatted capacity (for example, 2 MB for a standard 3½-inch HD floppy).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] It is implied that this should not be exceeded, since doing so will most likely result in performance problems.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] DMF was introduced permitting 1.68 MB to fit onto an otherwise standard 3½-inch disk; utilities then appeared allowing disks to be formatted as such.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Mixtures of decimal prefixes and binary sector sizes require care to properly calculate total capacity.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For example, 1.44 MB 3½-inch HD disks have the "M" prefix peculiar to their context, coming from their capacity of 2,880 512-byte sectors (1,440 KiB), consistent with neither a decimal megabyte nor a binary mebibyte (MiB).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Hence, these disks hold 1.47 MB or 1.41 MiB.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Usable data capacity is a function of the disk format used, which in turn is determined by the FDD controller and its settings.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Differences between such formats can result in capacities ranging from approximately 1,300 to 1,760 KiB (1.80 MB) on a standard 3½-inch high-density floppy (and up to nearly 2 MB with utilities such as 2M/2MGUI).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The highest capacity techniques require much tighter matching of drive head geometry between drives, something not always possible and unreliable.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For example, the LS-240 drive supports a 32 MB capacity on standard 3½-inch HD disks, but this is a write-once technique, and requires its own drive.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] The raw maximum transfer rate of 3½-inch ED floppy drives (2.88 MB) is nominally 1,000 kilobits/s, or approximately 83% that of single-speed CD-ROM (71% of audio CD).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] This represents the speed of raw data bits moving under the read head; however, the effective speed is somewhat less due to space used for headers, gaps and other format fields and can be even further reduced by delays to seek between tracks.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Floppy disks became commonplace during the 1980s and 1990s in their use with personal computers to distribute software, transfer data, and create backups.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Before hard disks became affordable to the general population, floppy disks were often used to store a computer's operating system (OS).
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Most home computers from that time have an elementary OS and BASIC stored in read-only memory (ROM), with the option of loading a more advanced OS from a floppy disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] By the early 1990s, the increasing software size meant large packages like Windows or Adobe Photoshop required a dozen disks or more.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] In 1996, there were an estimated five billion standard floppy disks in use.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] External USB-based floppy disk drives are still available, and many modern systems provide firmware support for booting from such drives.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] For more than two decades, the floppy disk was the primary external writable storage device used.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Most small computing environments before the 1990s were non-networked, and floppy disks were the primary means to transfer data between such computers, a method known informally as sneakernet.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Unlike hard disks, floppy disks were more commonly handled and seen, and typically novice users could identify a floppy disk.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Because of these factors, a picture of a 3½-inch floppy disk became an interface metaphor for saving data.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] As of 2026, the floppy disk symbol is still used by software on user-interface elements related to saving files even though physical floppy disks are largely obsolete.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] Examples of such software include LibreOffice, Microsoft Paint, and WordPad.
[src:digital-camera/3-5-floppy-disk] It is present in many UI symbol libraries and has a Unicode code point 💾 since 2010.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] In photography, the **35 mm equivalent focal length** is a measure of the angle of view for a particular combination of a camera lens and film or image sensor size.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The term is popular because in the early years of digital photography, most photographers experienced with interchangeable lenses were most familiar with the 35 mm film format.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] On any 35 mm film camera, a 28 mm lens is a wide-angle lens, and a 200 mm lens is a long-focus lens.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The 35 mm equivalent focal length of a particular lens–sensor combination is the focal length that one would need for a 35 mm film camera to obtain the same angle of view.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Two lens-sensor combinations with the same 35 mm equivalent focal length are expected to have the same angle of view.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Most commonly, the 35 mm equivalent focal length is based on equal *diagonal* angle of view.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This definition is also in the CIPA guideline DCG-001.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Alternatively, it may sometimes be based on *horizontal* angle of view.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] 35 mm equivalent focal lengths are calculated by multiplying the actual focal length of the lens by the crop factor of the sensor.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Quoted 35 mm equivalent focal lengths typically ignore depth of field (DOF), which depends on both focal length and aperture.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The DOF of smaller sensors is deeper at a given f number, due to the smaller absolute aperture diameters corresponding to shorter focal length lenses.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Equivalent depth of field can be calculated the same way using the crop factor.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For example, a 50mm f/2 lens on a 2× crop factor Micro Four Thirds camera would be equivalent to a 100 mm (= 2×50 mm) f/4 (= f/(2×2)) lens on a full-frame digital SLR in terms of field of view, depth of field, total light gathered, and diffraction effects.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However for the purposes of exposure calculations the aperture does not change for different sensor sizes.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] A standard 35 mm film image is 36 mm wide by 24 mm tall (35 mm refers to the height of the film including the perforations for film transport), and the diagonal is 43.3 mm.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For historical reasons, sensor size specifications such as 1/2.5" do not match the actual sensor size, but are a bit larger (typically about a factor of 1.5) than the actual sensor diagonal.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This is because these sensor size specifications refer to the size of a camera tube, while the usable sensor size is about 2/3 of the size of the tube.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Tubes are not used on digital cameras, but the same specifications are used.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Apart from the width- and diagonal-based 35 mm equivalent focal length definitions, there is a third definition: *EFL* = 50 *f* /*d* mm.
[src:digital-camera/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However, it is not clear to what extent this definition is used.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] In photography and computer vision, an **omnidirectional camera** (from "omni", meaning all), also known as **360-degree camera** (or **360° camera**), is a camera having a field of view that covers at least a full circle (360°) in the horizontal plane.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] It may be extended vertically up to a full sphere (1 spat), in which case it is also known as a **spherical camera**.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Omnidirectional cameras are important in applications where large visual field coverage is needed, such as in panoramic photography, VR photography, and robotics.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] A camera normally has a field of view that ranges from a few degrees to, at most, 180°.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] This means that it captures, at most, light falling onto the camera focal point through a hemisphere.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] In contrast, an *ideal* omnidirectional camera captures light from all directions falling onto the focal point, covering a full sphere.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] In practice, however, most omnidirectional cameras do not cover the entire sphere.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Many cameras which are referred to as omnidirectional cover the full 360° along the equator of the sphere but exclude the top and bottom.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] In the case that they do cover the full sphere, the captured light rays do not intersect exactly in a single focal point.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Various techniques can be used to generate 360-degree images.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] These models are used with a fisheye lens.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] The lens bends the angle of the shot to take a larger radius of the selected subject.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] It is not possible to take a complete 360-degree picture with this technique because there is always a dead angle directly behind the lens.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] 360-degree cameras with two lenses are probably the most common type, as they can accommodate a full 360-degree angle with two lenses facing each other.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] A camera takes pictures and videos with an angle of just over 180 degrees, e.g.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] These are then converted into a 360-degree object using software.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Problems are often caused by stitching errors that can happen at any given time.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] This means that an incorrect combination of the images can result in an unclean cut edge that is difficult or impossible to remove.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Depending on the application, manufacturers use more than two camera lenses to produce the images.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] One of the first cameras was Sony' Fourthview multihead camera and the throwing camera, Panono.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] It has 36 cameras, which are triggered at the same time at the highest point, if the camera was thrown into the air.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] The more lenses are installed in the camera, the more difficult it becomes for the software to combine the individual images, however, the possible stitching problems are less with a good stitching.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Camera rigs are mostly used for the attachment of 6 conventional Actioncams.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] GoPro produced one of the first camera rigs.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] They are available in different versions and connect several single cameras.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] The cameras are placed in this cube and record the surroundings in all directions.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] If several "normal" cameras are combined in a network, one speaks of mosaic-based cameras.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Each of these cameras records a small area of the environment.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] The individual images are then joined together like mosaic stones to form an omnidirectional overall image.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] The number of cameras to be used depends on the focal length of the lenses used.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] The smaller the focal length, the larger the angle of view and the fewer cameras are required.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Cars with omnidirectional camera include Nissan Qashqai, Volvo S90, Range Rover, Peugeot 3008 and Kia Stinger.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Traditional approaches to panoramic photography mainly consists of stitching shots taken separately into a single, continuous image.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] In contrast, an omnidirectional camera can be used to create panoramic art in real time, without the need for post processing, and will typically give much better quality products.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] In 2015 Facebook began rolling out omnidirectional videos where the user can view the video at any arbitrary camera angle around a 360-degree radius and limited tilt up-and-down angles.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] In robotics, omnidirectional cameras are frequently used for visual odometry and to solve simultaneous localization and mapping (SLAM) problems visually.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Due to its ability to capture a 360-degree view, better results can be obtained for optical flow and feature selection and matching.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Within the real estate industry, 360 camera technology has offered a way for prospective home buyers to tour the home without having to be there in person.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] An evolution inspired by an increasing amount of homes being purchased sight-unseen.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Some commercially available 360 cameras are sold with real estate as the main subject in mind.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Applications of omnidirectional cameras also include 3D reconstruction and surveillance, when it is important to cover as large a visual field as possible.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Microsoft RoundTable was introduced in 2007 for videoconferencing, where all participants on one location can be in the same image.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Several implementations of omnidirectional (360-degree) cameras exist, including two opposing fisheye lens configurations and cameras with more than 30 separate lenses.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] There have been fly-by-night companies that have produced prototypes and collected 'backers' on Kickstarter but have not delivered to end-users.
[src:digital-camera/360-degree-camera] Frequent new models and quality improvements in consumer-marketed 360-cameras are blurring the line between the professional and consumer market.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A **digital camera**, also called a **digicam**, is a camera that uses digital storage to capture images.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most cameras produced since the start of the 21st century are digital, largely replacing cameras that captured images on photographic film or film stock.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras are now integrated into mobile devices such as smartphones.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] However, high-end dedicated digital cameras are still commonly used by professionals.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras typically use a lens with an alterable diaphragm to focus light.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The diaphragm and shutter work to admit a controlled amount of light to the image.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This process is the same as previously-used film cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] However, digital cameras use an image pickup device that is electronic, compared to chemical.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Additionally, digital cameras can display images on a screen immediately after being recorded, and store and delete images from stored memory.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras can also record moving videos with sound.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some digital cameras have the ability to crop and stitch pictures and perform other kinds of image editing.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The first semiconductor image sensor was the charge-coupled device (CCD), invented by Willard S.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Smith at Bell Labs in 1969, based on MOS capacitor technology.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The NMOS active-pixel sensor was later invented by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985, which led to the development of the CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor) at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Lally of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory was thinking about how to use a mosaic photo sensor to capture digital images.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] His idea was to take pictures of the planets and stars while travelling through space to give information about the astronauts' position.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] As with Texas Instruments employee Willis Adcock's filmless camera (US patent 4,057,830) in 1972, the technology had yet to catch up with the concept.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 1972, the Landsat 1 satellite's multispectral scanner (MSS) started taking digital images of Earth.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The MSS, designed by Virginia Norwood at Hughes Aircraft Company starting in 1969, captured and transmitted image data from green, red, and two infrared bands with 6 bits per channel, using a mechanical rocking mirror and an array of 24 detectors.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Operating for six years, it transmitted more than 300,000 digital photographs of Earth while orbiting the planet about 14 times per day.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Also in 1972, Thomas McCord from MIT and James Westphal from Caltech together developed a digital camera for use with telescopes.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Their 1972 "photometer-digitizer system" used an analog-to-digital converter and a digital frame memory to store 256 x 256-pixel images of planets and stars, which were then recorded on digital magnetic tape.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] CCD sensors were not yet commercially available, and the camera used a silicon diode vidicon tube detector, which was cooled using dry ice to reduce dark current, allowing exposure times of up to one hour.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The Cromemco Cyclops was an all-digital camera introduced as a commercial product in 1975.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Its design was published as a hobbyist construction project in the February 1975 issue of *Popular Electronics* magazine.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] It used a 32×32 metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensor, which was a modified MOS dynamic RAM (DRAM) memory chip.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Steven Sasson, an engineer at Eastman Kodak, built a self-contained electronic camera that used a monochrome Fairchild Semiconductor CCD image sensor in 1975.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Around the same time, Fujifilm began developing CCD technology in the 1970s.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Early uses were mainly military and scientific, followed by medical and news applications.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The first filmless SLR (single lens reflex) camera was publicly demonstrated by Sony in August 1981.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The Sony Mavica (magnetic still video camera) used a color-striped 2/3" format CCD sensor with 280K pixels, along with analogue video signal processing and recording.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The Mavica electronic still camera recorded FM-modulated analog video signals on a newly developed 2" magnetic floppy disk, dubbed the "Mavipak".
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The disk format was later standardized as the "Still Video Floppy", or "SVF".
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The Canon RC-701, introduced in May 1986, was the first SVF camera (and the first electronic SLR camera) sold in the US.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] It employed an SLR viewfinder, included a 2/3" format color CCD sensor with 380K pixels, and was sold along with a removable 11-66mm and 50-150mm zoom lens.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Over the next few years, many other companies began selling SVF cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] These analog electronic cameras included the Nikon QV-1000C, which had an SLR viewfinder and a 2/3" format monochrome CCD sensor with 380K pixels and recorded analog black-and-white images on a Still Video Floppy.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] At Photokina 1988, Fujifilm introduced the FUJIX DS-1P, the first fully digital camera, which recorded digital images using a semiconductor memory card.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The camera's memory card had a capacity of 2 MB of SRAM (static random-access memory) and could hold up to ten photographs.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 1989, Fujifilm released the FUJIX DS-X, the first fully digital camera to be commercially released.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 1996, Toshiba's 40 MB flash memory card was adopted for several digital cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The first prototype camera phones were included in Isaac (camera phone), a personal digital assistant for people with intellectual disabilities which was deployed in 1994.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The first commercially available camera phone was the Kyocera Visual Phone VP-210, released in Japan in May 1999.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] It was called a "mobile videophone" at the time, and had a 110,000-pixel front-facing camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] It stored up to 20 JPEG digital images, which could be sent over e-mail, or the phone could send up to two images per second over Japan's Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) cellular network.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The Samsung SCH-V200, released in South Korea in June 2000, was also one of the first phones with a built-in camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] It had a TFT liquid-crystal display (LCD) and stored up to 20 digital photos at 350,000-pixel resolution.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] However, it could not send the resulting image over the telephone function but required a computer connection to access photos.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The first mass-market camera phone was the J-SH04, a Sharp J-Phone model sold in Japan in November 2000.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] It could instantly transmit pictures via cell phone telecommunication.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] By the mid-2000s, higher-end cell phones had an integrated digital camera, and by the early 2010s, almost all smartphones had an integrated digital camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In the early 2020's, a revival of digital cameras produced from the early 2000s that were produced prior to smartphones occurred as a TikTok trend and spread to other online marketplaces such as eBay and Etsy.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The trend was characterized by Gen Z nostalgia and a homage to the Y2K aesthetic.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The two major types of digital image sensors are CCD and CMOS.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A CCD sensor has one amplifier for all the pixels, while each pixel in a CMOS active-pixel sensor has its own amplifier.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Compared to CCDs, CMOS sensors use less power.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with a small sensor use a back-side-illuminated CMOS (BSI-CMOS) sensor.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The image processing capabilities of the camera determine the outcome of the final image quality much more than the sensor type.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor that turns light into discrete signals.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The brighter the image at a given point on the sensor, the larger the value that is read for that pixel.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Depending on the physical structure of the sensor, a color filter array may be used, which requires demosaicing to recreate a full-color image.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The number of pixels in the sensor determines the camera's "pixel count".
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In a typical sensor, the pixel count is the product of the number of rows and the number of columns.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] For example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares' resolution selector allows the user to optionally lower the resolution to reduce the file size per picture and extend lossless digital zooming.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The bottom resolution option is typically 640×480 pixels (0.3 megapixels).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] An image's sharpness is presented through the crisp detail, defined lines, and its depicted contrast.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Sharpness is a factor of multiple systems throughout the DSLR camera by its ISO, resolution, lens, and the lens settings, the environment of the image, and its post-processing.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Images have a possibility of being too sharp, but they can never be too in focus.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A digital camera resolution is determined by a digital sensor.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The digital sensor indicates a high level of sharpness can be produced through the amount of noise and grain that is tolerated through the lens of the camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Resolution within the field of digital stills and digital movies is indicated through the camera's ability to determine detail based on the distance, which is then measured by frame size, pixel type, number, and organization.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Although some DSLR cameras have limited resolutions, it is almost impossible to not have the proper sharpness for an image.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The ISO choice when taking a photo affects the quality of the image, as high ISO settings equate to an image that is less sharp due to the increased amount of noise allowed into the image, along with too little noise, which can also produce an image that is not sharp.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Since the first digital backs were introduced, there have been three main methods of capturing the image, each based on the hardware configuration of the sensor and color filters.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The third method is called *scanning* because the sensor moves across the focal plane much like the sensor of an image scanner.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The *linear* or *tri-linear* sensors in scanning cameras use only a single line of photosensors, or three lines for the three colors.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Scanning may be accomplished by moving the sensor (for example, when using color co-site sampling) or by rotating the whole camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A digital rotating line camera offers images consisting of a total resolution that is very high.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Improvements in single-shot cameras and image file processing at the beginning of the 21st century made single-shot cameras almost completely dominant, even in high-end commercial photography.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most current consumer digital cameras use a Bayer filter mosaic in combination with an optical anti-aliasing filter to reduce the aliasing due to the reduced sampling of the different primary-color images.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A demosaicing algorithm is used to interpolate color information to create a full array of RGB image data.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Cameras that use a beam-splitter single-shot 3CCD approach, three-filter multi-shot approach, color co-site sampling or Foveon X3 sensor do not use anti-aliasing filters, nor demosaicing.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A single sensor element cannot simultaneously record these three intensities, so a color filter array (CFA) must be used to selectively filter a particular color for each pixel.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The Bayer filter pattern is a repeating 2x2 mosaic pattern of light filters, with green ones at opposite corners and red and blue in the other two positions.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The high proportion of green takes advantage of the properties of the human visual system, which determines brightness mostly from green and is far more sensitive to brightness than to hue or saturation.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Sometimes a 4-color filter pattern is used, often involving two different hues of green.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] That provides potentially more accurate color, but requires a slightly more complicated interpolation process.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The color intensity values not captured for each pixel can be interpolated from the values of adjacent pixels which represent the color being calculated.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with digital image sensors that are smaller than the typical 35 mm film size have a smaller field or angle of view when used with a lens of the same focal length.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This is because the angle of view is a function of both focal length and the sensor or film size used.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The crop factor is relative to the 35mm film format.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] If a smaller sensor is used, as in most digicams, the field of view is cropped by the sensor to smaller than the 35 mm full-frame format's field of view.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This narrowing of the field of view may be described as crop factor, a factor by which a longer focal length lens would be needed to get the same field of view on a 35 mm film camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Full-frame digital SLRs use a sensor of the same size as a frame of 35 mm film.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Crop factors for non-SLR consumer compact and bridge cameras are larger, frequently 4x or more.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The resolution of a digital camera is often limited by the image sensor which turns light into discrete signals.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] **Pixels are square and is often equal to 1**, for example, a 1,000 by 1,000-pixel sensor would have 1,000,000 pixels, or 1 megapixel.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] On full-frame sensors (i.e., 24 mm 36 mm), some cameras propose images with 20–25 million pixels that were captured by 7.5–m photosites, or a surface that is 50 times larger.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Digital cameras come in a wide range of sizes, prices, and capabilities.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In addition to general-purpose digital cameras, specialized cameras including multispectral imaging equipment and astrographs are used for scientific, military, medical, and other special purposes.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are intended to be portable (pocketable) and are particularly suitable for casual "snapshots".
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Point-and-shoot cameras usually fall under this category.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many incorporate a retractable lens assembly that provides optical zoom.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In most models, an auto-actuating lens cover protects the lens from elements.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most ruggedized or water-resistant models do not retract, and most with superzoom capability do not retract fully.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Compact cameras are usually designed to be easy to use.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Almost all include an automatic mode, or "auto mode", which automatically makes all camera settings for the user.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Compact digital cameras typically contain a small sensor that trades-off picture quality for compactness and simplicity; images can usually only be stored using lossy compression (JPEG).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most have a built-in flash usually of low power, sufficient for nearby subjects.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A few high-end compact digital cameras have a hot shoe for connecting to an external flash.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Live preview is almost always used to frame the photo on an integrated LCD.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In addition to being able to take still photographs almost all compact cameras have the ability to record video.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Compacts often have macro capability and zoom lenses, but the zoom range (up to 30x) is generally enough for candid photography but less than is available on bridge cameras (more than 60x), or the interchangeable lenses of DSLR cameras available at a much higher cost.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus systems in compact digital cameras generally are based on a contrast-detection methodology using the image data from the live preview feed of the main imager.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some compact digital cameras use a hybrid autofocus system similar to what is commonly available on DSLRs.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Typically, compact digital cameras incorporate a nearly silent leaf shutter into the lens but play a simulated camera sound for skeuomorphic purposes.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] For low cost and small size, the cameras typically use image sensor formats with a diagonal between 6 and 11 mm, corresponding to a crop factor between 7 and 4.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This gives them weaker low-light performance, greater depth of field, generally closer focusing ability, and smaller components than cameras using larger sensors.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some cameras use a larger sensor including, at the high end, a pricey full-frame sensor compact camera, such as Sony Cyber-shot DSC-RX1, but have the capability near that of a DSLR.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A variety of additional features are available depending on the model of the camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Such features include GPS, compass, barometers and altimeters.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Starting in 2010, some compact digital cameras can take 3D still photos.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] These 3D compact stereo cameras are able to capture 3D panoramic photos with dual lens or even a single lens for playback on a 3D TV.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, Sony released two add-on camera models without display, to be used with a smartphone or tablet, controlled by a mobile application via WiFi.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Rugged compact cameras typically include protection against submersion, hot and cold conditions, shock, and pressure.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Terms used to describe such properties include waterproof, freeze-proof, heatproof, shockproof, and crushproof, respectively.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Nearly all major camera manufacturers have at least one product in this category.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some are waterproof to a considerable depth up to 100 feet (30 m); others only 10 feet (3 m), but only a few will float.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Ruggeds often lack some of the features of ordinary compact camera, but they have video capability and the majority can record sound.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most have image stabilization and built-in flash.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Touchscreen LCD and GPS do not work underwater.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] GoPro and other brands offer action cameras which are rugged, small, and can be easily attached to helmets, arms, bicycles, etc.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most have a wide angle and fixed focus and can take still pictures and video, typically with sound.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The 360-degree camera can take picture or video 360 degrees using two lenses back-to-back and shooting at the same time.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some of the cameras are Ricoh Theta S, Nikon Keymission 360 and Samsung Gear 360.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Nico360 was launched in 2016 and claimed as the world's smallest 360-degree camera with size 46 x 46 x 28 mm (1.8 x 1.8 x 1.1 in) and price less than $200.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] With virtual reality mode built-in stitching, Wifi, and Bluetooth, live streaming can be done.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Due to it also being water resistant, the Nico360 can be used as action camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras physically resemble DSLRs, and are sometimes called DSLR-shape or DSLR-like.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] They provide some similar features but, like compacts, they use a fixed lens and a small sensor.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some compact cameras have also PSAM mode.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most use live preview to frame the image.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Their usual autofocus is by the same contrast-detect mechanism as compacts, but many bridge cameras have a manual focus mode and some have a separate focus ring for greater control.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The big physical size and small sensor allow superzoom and wide aperture.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Bridge cameras generally include an image stabilization system to enable longer handheld exposures, sometimes better than DSLR for low light conditions.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Sony RX10) or 400 mm (variable aperture, e.g.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix FZ1000) equivalent, corresponding to an optical zoom factor of roughly 10 to 15.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some bridge cameras have a lens thread to attach accessories such as wide-angle or telephoto converters as well as filters such as UV or Circular Polarizing filter and lens hoods.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The scene is composed by viewing the display or the electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most have a slightly longer shutter lag than a DSLR.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many of these cameras can store images in a raw format in addition to supporting JPEG.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The majority have a built-in flash, but only a few have a hotshoe.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In bright sun, the quality difference between a good compact camera and a digital SLR is minimal but bridge cameras are more portable, cost less and have a greater zoom ability.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Thus a bridge camera may better suit outdoor daytime activities, except when seeking professional-quality photos.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In late 2008, a new type of camera emerged, called a *mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera*.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] It is technically a DSLR camera that does not require a reflex mirror, a key component of the former.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] While a typical DSLR has a mirror that reflects light from the lens up to the optical viewfinder, in a mirrorless camera, there is no optical viewfinder.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The image sensor is exposed to light at all times, giving the user a digital preview of the image either on the built-in rear LCD screen or an electronic viewfinder (EVF).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] These are simpler and more compact than DSLRs due to not having a lens reflex system.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some MILCs have a separate electronic viewfinder to compensate the lack of an optical one.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In other cameras, the back display is used as the primary viewfinder in the same way as in compact cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] One disadvantage of mirrorless cameras compared to a typical DSLR is its battery life due to the energy consumption of the electronic viewfinder, but this can be mitigated by a setting inside the camera in some models.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Olympus and Panasonic released many Micro Four-Thirds cameras with interchangeable lenses that are fully compatible with each other without any adapter, while others have proprietary mounts.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2014, Kodak released its first Micro Four Third system camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] As of March 2014, mirrorless cameras are fast becoming appealing to both amateurs and professionals alike due to their simplicity, compatibility with some DSLR lenses, and features that match most DSLRs today.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] While most digital cameras with interchangeable lenses feature a lens-mount of some kind, there are also a number of modular cameras, where the shutter and sensor are incorporated into the lens module.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The first such modular camera was the Minolta Dimâge V in 1996, followed by the Minolta Dimâge EX 1500 in 1998 and the Minolta MetaFlash 3D 1500 in 1999.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2009, Ricoh released the Ricoh GXR modular camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] At CES 2013, Sakar International announced the Polaroid iM1836, an 18MP camera with 1"-sensor with interchangeable sensor-lens.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] An adapter for Micro Four-Thirds, Nikon and K-mount lenses was planned to ship with the camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] There are also a number of add-on camera modules for smartphones, they are called *lens-style* cameras (lens camera or smart lens).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] They contain all the essential components of a digital camera inside a DSLR lens-shaped module, hence the name, but lack any sort of viewfinder and most controls of a regular camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Instead, they are connected wirelessly and/or mounted to a smartphone to be used as its display output and operate the camera's various controls.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLR) is a camera with a digital sensor that uses a reflex mirror to split or direct light into the viewfinder to produce an image.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The reflex mirror finds the image by blocking light to the camera's sensor and then reflecting it into the camera's pentaprism which allows it to be seen through the viewfinder.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] When the shutter release is fully pressed the reflex mirror pulls out horizontally below the pentaprism briefly darkening the viewfinder and then opening up the sensor for exposure which creates the photo.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The digital image is produced by the sensor which is an array of photoreceptors on a microchip capable of recording light values.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many modern DSLRs offer the ability for "live view" or the framing of the subject emitted from the sensor onto a digital screen, and many have a hotshoe.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The sensor also known as a **full-frame sensor** is much larger than the other types, typically 18mm to 36mm on the diagonal (crop factor 2, 1.6, or 1).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The larger sensor permits more light to be received by each pixel; this, combined with the relatively large lenses provides superior low-light performance.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] For the same field of view and the same aperture, a larger sensor gives shallower focus.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs can equip interchangeable lenses for versatility by removing it from the lens mount of the camera, typically a silver ring on the front side of DSLRs.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] These lenses work in tandem with the mechanics of the DSLR to adjust aperture and focus.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Autofocus is accomplished using sensors in the mirror box and on most modern lenses can be activated from the lens itself which will trigger upon shutter release.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2025, a variety of lower-cost medium format digital cameras were available in the 50 to 100MP resolution range.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Digital Still Camera (DSC), such as the Sony DSC cameras, is a type of camera that does not use a reflex mirror.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] DSCs are like point-and-shoot cameras and are the most common type of cameras, due to their comfortable price and its quality.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Cameras with fixed semi-transparent mirrors, also known as DSLT cameras, such as the Sony SLT cameras, are single-lens without a moving reflex mirror as in a conventional DSLR.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A semi-transparent mirror transmits some of the light to the image sensor and reflects some of the light along the path to an autofocus sensor.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The total amount of light is not changed, just some of the light travels one path and some of it travels the other.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The consequences are that DSLT cameras should shoot a half stop differently from DSLR.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] One advantage of using a DSLT camera is the blind moments a DSLR user experiences while the reflecting mirror is moved to send the light to the sensor instead of the viewfinder.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The "blackouts" do not exist for DSLT cameras since they use an EVF (electronic viewfinder).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Since there is no time at which light is not traveling along both paths, DSLT cameras get the benefit of continuous autofocus tracking.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This is especially beneficial for burst-mode shooting in low-light conditions and also for tracking when taking video.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A rangefinder is a device to measure subject distance, with the intent to adjust the focus of a camera's objective lens accordingly (open-loop controller).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The rangefinder and lens focusing mechanism may or may not be coupled.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In common parlance, the term "rangefinder camera" is interpreted very narrowly to denote manual-focus cameras with a visually-read out optical rangefinder based on parallax.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most digital cameras achieve focus through analysis of the image captured by the objective lens and distance estimation, if it is provided at all, is only a byproduct of the focusing process (closed-loop controller).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A line-scan camera traditionally has a single row of pixel sensors, instead of a matrix of them.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The lines are continuously fed to a computer that joins them to each other and makes an image.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] That is most commonly done by connecting the camera output to a frame grabber which resides in a PCI slot of an industrial computer.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The frame grabber acts to buffer the image and sometimes provide some processing before delivering to the computer software for processing.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Industrial processes often require height and width measurements performed by digital line-scan systems.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Multiple rows of sensors may be used to make colored images, or to increase sensitivity by TDI (time delay and integration).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many industrial applications require a wide field of view.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Traditionally maintaining consistent light over large 2D areas is quite difficult.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] With a line scan camera all that is necessary is to provide even illumination across the "line" currently being viewed by the camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This makes sharp pictures of objects that pass the camera at high speed.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Such cameras are also commonly used to make photo finishes, to determine the winner when multiple competitors cross the finishing line at nearly the same time.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] They can also be used as industrial instruments for analyzing fast processes.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are also extensively used in imaging from satellites (see push broom scanner).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In this case the row of sensors is perpendicular to the direction of satellite motion.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Line-scan cameras are widely used in scanners.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In this case, the camera moves horizontally.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Superzoom cameras are cameras fitted with a variable focal length lens, typically ranging from a wide-angle focal length to a super-telephoto focal length.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This type of digital camera captures information about the light field emanating from a scene; that is the intensity of light in a scene, and also the direction that the light rays are traveling in space.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This contrasts with a conventional digital camera, which records only light intensity.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Instead of measuring the intensity of light over some predetermined time interval (the exposure time), event cameras detect when the intensity of light changes by some threshold for each pixel independently, usually with microsecond precision.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many devices have a built-in digital camera, including, for example, smartphones, mobile phones, PDAs and laptop computers.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Built-in cameras generally store the images in the JPEG file format, although cameras in Apple's iPhone line have used the HEIC format since 2017.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Mobile phones incorporating digital cameras were introduced in Japan in 2001 by J-Phone.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2003 camera phones outsold stand-alone digital cameras, and in 2006 they outsold film and digital stand-alone cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Five billion camera phones were sold in five years, and by 2007 more than half of the installed base of all mobile phones were camera phones.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Sales of separate cameras peaked in 2008.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Several manufacturers lead in digital camera (commonly DSLRs) production.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Each brand embodies different mission statements that differentiate it from the others besides the equipment it manufactures.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Most manufacturers share modern features in the cameras they produce.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] However, some specialize in specific details, either physically on camera or within the system and image quality.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Sales of traditional digital cameras have declined due to the increasing use of smartphones for casual photography, which also enable easier manipulation and sharing of photos through the use of apps and web-based services.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] "Bridge cameras", in contrast, have held their ground with functionality that most smartphone cameras lack, such as optical zoom and other advanced features.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] DSLRs have also lost ground to Mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera (MILC)s offering the same sensor size in a smaller camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A few expensive ones use a full-frame sensor, just like DSLR professional cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In response to the convenience and flexibility of smartphone cameras, some manufacturers produced "smart" digital cameras that combine features of traditional cameras with those of a smartphone.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2012, Nikon and Samsung released the Coolpix S800c and Galaxy Camera, the first two digital cameras to run the Android operating system.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Since this software platform is used in many smartphones, they can integrate with some of the same services (such as e-mail attachments, social networks and photo sharing sites) that smartphones do and use other Android-compatible software.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In an inversion, some phone makers have introduced smartphones with cameras designed to resemble traditional digital cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Nokia released the 808 PureView and Lumia 1020 in 2012 and 2013; the two devices respectively run the Symbian and Windows Phone operating systems, and both include a 41-megapixel camera (along with a camera grip attachment for the latter).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Similarly, Samsung introduced the Galaxy S4 Zoom, having a 16-megapixel camera and 10x optical zoom, combining traits from the Galaxy S4 Mini with the Galaxy Camera.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Panasonic Lumix DMC-CM1 is an Android KitKat 4.4 smartphone with 20MP, 1" sensor, the largest sensor for a smartphone ever, with Leica fixed lens equivalent of 28 mm at F2.8, can take RAW image and 4K video, has 21 mm thickness.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Furthermore, in 2018 Huawei P20 Pro is an android Oreo 8.1 has triple Leica lenses in the back of the smartphone with 40MP 1/1.7" RGB sensor as first lens, 20MP 1/2.7" monochrome sensor as second lens and 8MP 1/4" RGB sensor with 3x optical zoom as third lens.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Combination of first lens and second lens will produce bokeh image with larger high dynamic range, whereas combination of mega pixel first lens and optical zoom will produce maximum 5x digital zoom without loss of quality by reducing the image size to 8MP.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] After a big dip of sales in 2012, consumer digital camera sales declined again in 2013 by 36 percent.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2011, compact digital cameras sold 10 million per month.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2013, sales fell to about 4 million per month.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] DSLR and MILC sales also declined in 2013 by 10–15% after almost ten years of double digit growth.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Worldwide unit sales of digital cameras is continuously declining from 148 million in 2011 to 58 million in 2015 and tends to decrease more in the following years.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Film camera sales hit their peak at about 37 million units in 1997, while digital camera sales began in 1989.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] By 2008, the film camera market had died and digital camera sales hit their peak at 121 million units in 2010.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2002, cell phones with an integrated camera had been introduced and in 2003 the cell phone with an integrated camera had sold 80 million units per year.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] By 2011, cell phones with an integrated camera were selling hundreds of millions per year, which were causing a decline in digital cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In 2015, digital camera sales were 35 million units or only less than a third of digital camera sales numbers at their peak and also slightly less than film camera sold number at their peak.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] A common alternative is the use of a card reader which may be capable of reading several types of storage media, as well as high speed transfer of data to the computer.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Use of a card reader also avoids draining the camera battery during the download process.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] An external card reader allows convenient direct access to the images on a collection of storage media.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] But if only one storage card is in use, moving it back and forth between the camera and the reader can be inconvenient.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many computers have a card reader built in, at least for SD cards.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many modern cameras support the PictBridge standard, which allows them to send data directly to a PictBridge-capable printer without the need for a computer.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] PictBridge uses PTP to transfer images and control information.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Wireless connectivity can also provide for printing photos without a cable connection.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] An *instant-print camera*, is a digital camera with a built-in printer.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] This confers a similar functionality as an instant camera which uses instant film to quickly generate a physical photograph.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Such non-digital cameras were popularized by Polaroid with the SX-70 in 1972.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras include a video output port.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Usually sVideo, it sends a standard-definition video signal to a television, allowing the user to show one picture at a time.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Buttons or menus on the camera allow the user to select the photo, advance from one to another, or automatically send a "slide show" to the TV.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] HDMI has been adopted by many high-end digital camera makers, to show photos in their high-resolution quality on an HDTV.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] In January 2008, Silicon Image announced a new technology for sending video from mobile devices to a television in digital form.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] MHL sends pictures as a video stream, up to 1080p resolution, and is compatible with HDMI.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some DVD recorders and television sets can read memory cards used in cameras; alternatively several types of flash card readers have TV output capability.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Cameras can be equipped with a varying amount of environmental sealing to provide protection against splashing water, moisture (humidity and fog), dust and sand, or complete waterproofness to a certain depth and for a certain duration.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The latter is one of the approaches to allow underwater photography, the other approach being the use of waterproof housings.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many waterproof digital cameras are also shockproof and resistant to low temperatures.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Some waterproof cameras can be fitted with a waterproof housing to increase the operational depth range.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] The Olympus 'Tough' range of compact cameras is an example.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Many digital cameras have preset modes for different applications.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Within the constraints of correct exposure various parameters can be changed, including exposure, aperture, focusing, light metering, white balance, and equivalent sensitivity.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] For example, a portrait might use a wider aperture to render the background out of focus, and would seek out and focus on a human face rather than other image content.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Few cameras are equipped with a voice note (audio-only) recording feature.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p01] Firmwares may be equipped with the ability to select a suitable scene mode automatically through artificial intelligence.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Many camera phones and most stand alone digital cameras store image data in flash memory cards or other removable media.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Most stand-alone cameras use SD format, while a few use CompactFlash, CFexpress or other types.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] In January 2012, a faster XQD card format was announced.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] In early 2014, some high end cameras have two hot-swappable memory slots.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Photographers can swap one of the memory card with camera-on.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Each memory slot can accept either Compact Flash or SD Card.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] All new Sony cameras also have two memory slots, one for its Memory Stick and one for SD Card, but not hot-swapable.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The approximate count of remaining photos until space exhaustion is calculated by the firmware throughout use and indicated in the viewfinder, to prepare the user for an impending necessary hot swap of the memory card, and/or file offload.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] A few cameras used other removable storage such as Microdrives (very small hard disk drives), CD single (185 MB), and 3.5" floppy disks (e. g.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Most manufacturers of digital cameras do not provide drivers and software to allow their cameras to work with Linux or other free software.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Still, many cameras use the standard USB mass storage and/or Media Transfer Protocol, and are thus widely supported.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Other cameras are supported by the gPhoto project, and many computers are equipped with a memory card reader.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The Joint Photography Experts Group standard (JPEG) is the most common file format for storing image data.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Other file types include Tagged Image File Format (TIFF), High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF), and various Raw image formats.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Many cameras, especially high-end ones, support a raw image format.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] A raw image is the unprocessed set of pixel data directly from the camera's sensor, often saved in a proprietary format.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Adobe Systems has released the DNG format, a royalty-free raw image format used by at least 10 camera manufacturers.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Raw files initially had to be processed in specialized image editing programs, but over time many mainstream editing programs, such as Google's Picasa, have added support for raw images.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Rendering to standard images from raw sensor data allows more flexibility in making major adjustments without losing image quality or retaking the picture.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Formats for movies are AVI, DV, MPEG, MOV (often containing motion JPEG), WMV, and ASF (basically the same as WMV).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Recent formats include MP4, which is based on the QuickTime format and uses newer compression algorithms to allow longer recording times in the same space.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Other formats that are used in cameras (but not for pictures) are the Design Rule for Camera Format (DCF), an ISO specification, used in almost all camera since 1998, which defines an internal file structure and naming.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Also used is the Digital Print Order Format (DPOF), which dictates what order images are to be printed in and how many copies.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The DCF 1998 defines a logical file system with 8.3 filenames and makes the usage of either FAT12, FAT16, FAT32 or exFAT mandatory for its physical layer to maximize platform interoperability.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Most cameras include Exif data that provides metadata about the picture.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Exif data may include aperture, exposure time, focal length, date and time taken.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] To guarantee interoperability, DCF specifies the file system for image and sound files to be used on formatted DCF media (like removable or non-removable memory) as FAT12, FAT16, FAT32, or exFAT.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Media with a capacity of more than 2 GB must be formatted using FAT32 or exFAT.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] These directories contain files with names such as "ABCD1234.JPG" that consist of four alphanumeric characters (often "100_", "DSC0", "DSCF", "IMG_", "MOV_", or "P000"), followed by a number.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Handling of directories with possibly user-created duplicate numbers may vary among camera firmwares.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] DCF 2.0 adds support for DCF optional files recorded in an optional color space (that is, Adobe RGB rather than sRGB).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Such files must be indicated by a leading "_" (as in "_DSC" instead of "100_" or "DSC0").
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] To enable loading many images in miniature view quickly and efficiently, and to retain meta data, some vendors' firmwares generate accompanying low-resolution thumbnail files for videos and raw photos.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] For example, those of Canon cameras end with `.THM`.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] JPEG can already store a thumbnail image standalone.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras have become smaller over time, resulting in an ongoing need to develop a battery small enough to fit in the camera and yet able to power it for a reasonable length of time.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras use either proprietary or standard consumer batteries.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] As of March 2014, most cameras use proprietary lithium-ion batteries while some use standard AA batteries or primarily use a proprietary Lithium-ion rechargeable battery pack but have an optional AA battery holder available.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The most common class of battery used in digital cameras is proprietary battery formats.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] These are built to a manufacturer's custom specifications.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Almost all proprietary batteries are lithium-ion.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] In addition to being available from the OEM, aftermarket replacement batteries are commonly available for most camera models.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Digital cameras which use off-the-shelf batteries are typically designed to be able to use both single-use disposable and rechargeable batteries, but not with both types in use at the same time.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The most common off-the-shelf battery size used is AA.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] CR2, CR-V3 batteries, and AAA batteries are also used in some cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The CR2 and CR-V3 batteries are lithium based, intended for a single use.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Rechargeable RCR-V3 lithium-ion batteries are also available as an alternative to non-rechargeable CR-V3 batteries.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Some battery grips for DSLRs come with a separate holder to accommodate AA cells as an external power source.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] When digital cameras became common, many photographers asked whether their film cameras could be converted to digital.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The answer was not immediately clear, as it differed among models.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] For the majority of 35 mm film cameras the answer is no, the reworking and cost would be too great, especially as lenses have been evolving as well as cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] For most a conversion to digital, to give enough space for the electronics and allow a liquid crystal display to preview, would require removing the back of the camera and replacing it with a custom built digital unit.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Many early professional SLR cameras, such as the Kodak DCS series, were developed from 35 mm film cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The technology of the time, however, meant that rather than being digital "backs" the bodies of these cameras were mounted on large, bulky digital units, often bigger than the camera portion itself.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] These were factory built cameras, however, not aftermarket conversions.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] A notable exception is the Nikon E2 and Nikon E3, using additional optics to convert the 35 mm format to a 2/3 CCD-sensor.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] A few 35 mm cameras have had digital camera backs made by their manufacturer, Leica being a notable example with the Leica R8–R9.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Medium format and large format cameras (those using film stock greater than 35 mm), have a low unit production, and typical digital backs for them cost over $10,000.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] These cameras also tend to be highly modular, with handgrips, film backs, winders, and lenses available separately to fit various needs.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The very large sensor these backs use leads to enormous image sizes.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One's P45 39 MP image back creates a single TIFF image of size up to 224.6 MB, and even greater pixel counts are available.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Medium format digitals such as this are geared more towards studio and portrait photography than their smaller DSLR counterparts; the ISO speed in particular tends to have a maximum of 400, versus 6400 for some DSLR cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] (Canon EOS-1D Mark IV and Nikon D3S have ISO 12800 plus Hi-3 ISO 102400 with the Canon EOS-1Dx's ISO of 204800).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] In the industrial and high-end professional photography market, some camera systems use modular (removable) image sensors.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] For example, some medium format SLR cameras, such as the Mamiya 645D series, allow installation of either a digital camera back or a traditional photographic film back.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Linear array cameras are also called scan backs.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Most earlier digital camera backs used linear array sensors, moving vertically to digitize the image.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Many of them only capture grayscale images.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The relatively long exposure times, in the range of seconds or even minutes generally limit scan backs to studio applications, where all aspects of the photographic scene are under the photographer's control.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Some other camera backs use CCD arrays similar to typical cameras.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Since it is much easier to manufacture a high-quality linear CCD array with only thousands of pixels than a CCD matrix with millions, very high resolution linear CCD camera backs were available much earlier than their CCD matrix counterparts.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] For example, you could buy an (albeit expensive) camera back with over 7,000 pixel horizontal resolution in the mid-1990s.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] However, as of 2004, it is still difficult to buy a comparable CCD matrix camera of the same resolution.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Rotating line cameras, with about 10,000 color pixels in its sensor line, are able, as of 2005, to capture about 120,000 lines during one full 360-degree rotation, thereby creating a single digital image of 1,200 Megapixels.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] Most modern digital camera backs use CCD or CMOS matrix sensors.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] The matrix sensor captures the entire image frame at once, instead of incrementing scanning the frame area through the prolonged exposure.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] For example, Phase One produces a 39 million pixel digital camera back with a 49.1 × 36.8 mm CCD in 2008.
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] This CCD array is a little smaller than a frame of 120 film and much larger than a 35 mm frame (36 × 24 mm).
[src:digital-camera/digital-camera-p02] In comparison, consumer digital cameras use arrays ranging from 36 × 24 mm (full frame on high end consumer DSLRs) to 1.28 × 0.96 mm (on camera phones) CMOS sensor.
